Actually you can use @Autowired JobRegistry and then your &quot;jobRegistryBeanPostProcessor&quot; will look something like this:

       @Autowired
       JobRegistry jr;

       @Bean
       public JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor jobRegistryBeanPostProcessor() {
       JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor postProcessor = new JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor();
       postProcessor.setJobRegistry(jr);
       return postProcessor;
   }

To stop a job programmatically you need to track your jobs by registering through the `JobRegistry`. When &#39;spring-batch&#39; is activated, for example by `@EnableBatchProcessing` an instance of `JobRegistry` is registered into the IoC and it&#39;s available for dependency injection; so you could &quot;`@Autowired`&quot; when you need.

To register a job you could:

 1. Use `JobRegistry#register` explicitly to add your jobs manually
 2. Register a `JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor` into the IoC. The processor is going to automatically register all the Job available from the IoC. This means all the bean and components which a registered into Spring IoC are added by default. Example:
```
// First register into IoC the JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor
// Do not forget to set its registry with the SpringBatch jobRegistry instance
@Bean 
public JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor jobRegistryBeanPostProcessor(JobRegistry jobRegistry) {
	 final JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor answer = new JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor();
	 answer.setJobRegistry(jobRegistry);
	 return answer;
	}
```

```
@Bean // This one is registered
public Job helloWorldJob() {
      return jobFactory.get(&quot;helloWorld&quot;)
             ...
             .build();
}
```
```
@Component // This one is registered automatically
public class HelloWorldJob implements Job {
 ...
}
```
```
public void runHelloWorldJob() {
// this one is not registered automatically because is not registered into IoC. 
// You need to explicitly add it manually
 Job hello = jobFactory.get(&quot;helloWorld&quot;)
             ...
             .build();
 jobLauncher.run(hello, ...); 
}
```

